Semilarski v. Prosecutor's Office: the cassation of the former vice-mayor of Tartu will be considered on August 4
This means that the decision on it is likely to be made in early September.
The courts of the first two instances to consider the lawsuit Semilarski refused, but in April his cassation complaint was accepted in the proceedings of the State Court.
On December 12, 2019, the Tartu Administrative Court returned the complaint to the applicant, as its permission does not fall within its jurisdiction of the Administrative Court.
The court's decision stated that the complaint contained a claim for compensation for damages caused in the course of criminal proceedings.
“The prosecutor’s office and the district court should regulate such issues,” said Tartu Courts spokeswoman Annette Kreitsmann.
According to her, Valvo Semilarski appealed this decision in the district court, which on February 5 did not change the decision of the court of first instance.
Now the State will have to say its word.
According to Semilarsky’s lawyer, Oliver Nyas, his client was unreasonably suspected of bribery for about two years.
He now demands that the prosecutor ' s office refute false allegations against him and compensate him for the moral damage.
The reason for the complaint to the court was the statements made by the prosecutor for special cases of the Lyuna District Prosecutor's Office Margus Gross in October 2017, when Semilarski, together with the then Vice Mayor of Tartu Artem Suvorov, was arrested on suspicion of committing several crimes.
“When I was arrested, the Security Police and the Prosecutor’s Office immediately organized a press conference and informed the entire Republic of Estonia that the leaders of Tartu – one of the most influential bodies of local self-governments – are being sold.
These public suspicions in the air have been with me for about two years.
And now that these allegations and suspicions have turned out to be false, the prosecutor’s office does not want to say anything about it,” Semilarski commented in early August 2019.
According to Oliver Nyaes, at a press conference, the prosecutor went beyond the legal framework in which the prosecutor's office should operate.
“The allegations of bribery and bribery turned out to be false, but that’s not the only problem here.
The European Court of Human Rights, for example, has repeatedly stressed in its rulings on Russia, as well as on Lithuania, that at the stage of the investigation, the representatives of the state must be careful when choosing words so that suspects are not presented as criminals before the sentence is handed down.
The prosecutor’s office is also bound by the presumption of innocence, which, unfortunately, was not observed in this case against Valvo Semilarski,” he said.
"The public presentation of Semilarski as a serious offender and a briber in circumstances where the facts underlying the suspicion of bribery are still being ascertained is unacceptable, which contradicts the presumption of innocence and is unfair in relation to the statement."
According to rus.err.ee, former deputy mayor Tartu Valvo Semilarski will not be prosecuted on charges of bribery – the criminal case against him was partially closed in July.
At the same time, the former official is being tried on charges of deliberately violating anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions of particularly large size.
According to the indictment, in the period from 2015 to 2017, the former deputy mayor of Tartu participated more than thirty times in the meetings of the city administration in making decisions related to companies operating in Tartu, with the owners or managers of which Semilarski actively communicated at the personal level.
According to Gross, in all these cases Semilarski had personal interests, and therefore he had to refrain from participating in the decision-making.
Previously, as wrote rus.err.ee, the prosecutor’s office has presented Semilarsky with suspicions of bribery and violation of anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions of particularly large size.
This happened in October 2016, when he was arrested along with another deputy mayor Artem Suvorov (Centre Party).
The prosecutor’s office and the security police said there was strong evidence against the two vice-mayors.
After that, both officials resigned.
Suvorov's case later came to a court, which was fully justified by politics.
The trial of Valvo Semilarski is still ongoing.
