How the ECB’s decision to lower the key rate will affect the economy
The Bank of Russia is expected to lower the key rate again.
It fell another 0.25 percentage point, to 4.25% per annum - formally another historical minimum.
Judging by the return of a short step of the rate cut, as well as the tonality of the ECB’s statements and updated forecasts for the Russian economy, the regulator looks at the economic prospects more optimistic than before.
This means that the current cycle of monetary policy mitigation may soon stop.
“We have continued to soften monetary policy, primarily given that the risks of deflecting inflation still remain below 4% in 2021,” the head of the Bank of Russia, Elvira Nabiullina, said in a statement.
They are associated with a significant decrease in economic activity, a fall in domestic and foreign demand.
The recovery of the economy, Nabiullina said, will take more than a year and a half.
At the same time, she noted that after the lifting of restrictions due to the pandemic, economic processes revived: energy consumption, consumer and investment demand were restored, construction and production of consumer goods were expanded, the annual rate of decrease in freight traffic, industrial production slowed.
According to the ECB’s revised forecast, the economy will shrink 4.5-5.5% in 2020 (previously 4-6% expected), and the recovery growth in 2021 will be 3.5-4.5%, in 2022 - 2.5-3.5%.
In addition, the Bank of Russia revised its forecast for annual oil prices to $38 and $40 per barrel of Urals in 2020 and 2021, respectively.
Previously, the Central Bank had expected $27 and $35 per barrel.
Finally, the Bank of Russia’s inflation forecast for 2020 was 3.7-4.2% against the previously expected 3.8-4.8%.
The Bank of Russia’s view of the situation in the economy is becoming more optimistic, which brings us closer to the end of the mitigation cycle, according to the economists on Russia and the CIS “Renaissance Capital” Sofia Donetsk and Andrey Melashenko.
Thus, the Bank of Russia consistently lowers the key rate more than a year, since the beginning of last summer it has fallen by 3.5 percentage points.
And at the last meeting in June, the ECB immediately lowered it by one percentage point due to low inflation rates due to suppressed demand and the need to stimulate a slowed-down economy due to the pandemic and its associated constraints.
The chances for monetary policy adjustment are still there (at the next meeting on September 18 and until the end of the year), but the limit is already close, the chief analyst of Rosbank Evgeny Koshelev agrees.
The set of pro-inflation risks also points to a near pause in mitigating interest policy – disrupted supply chains, possible cost increases due to epidemic prevention measures, and faster (compared to expectations) recovery in demand, he says.
In addition, the Bank of Russia’s subsequent actions will require more attention to inflationary processes during the harvesting season, as well as external volatility, which has increased against the background of geopolitical conflicts.
Either way, the reduction in the key rate will lead to a further reduction in rates for the most reliable borrowers, as well as possibly on a mortgage, says senior economist of the analytical management of Otkritie Bank Maxim Petronevich.
The rate adjustment will be less pronounced than the reduction in the key rate, he clarifies.
Interest rates on consumer loans may fall by another 0.3-0.6 percentage point during the second half of the year, mortgage rates may end the year in the range of 6.2-7%, does not exclude economist BKS Prime Minister Anton Pokatovich.
The average rates on deposits, in his opinion, will also fall - in the coming months they can fall to 4.2-4.5% (now barely above 4.5%).
