The actor of the Russian series responded to the accusations of "LGBT propaganda and feminism"
The actor of the Russian TV series Chiki, whose creators were accused of “LGBT propaganda and feminism,” responded to the film’s claims.
The authors “understood the sharpness of the raised themes and did not want to offend anyone,” said American Stephen Thomas Oxner in an interview with the publication “The Rise.”
“It seems to me that this is a story about the power and common aspects of human life.
It has nothing to do with LGBT and feminism,” said the actor, who played the father of the boy who was changing into women’s clothing.
He said he was “proud of the job” and did not consider it propaganda.
At the same time, the American added, he is afraid of the reaction of some people to the storyline of the series: for example, there was a case when "a man in deep intoxication shot a set and said that all this was not true".
Then there were a couple of cases when we met disgruntled locals who didn’t understand what we were doing.
But we were open, so the people who first came with complaints began to help us,” he summed up.
The shooting took place in September 2019 in Kabardino-Balkaria: a drunken man attacked a car of the filming group with a gun, after which he was detained by police officers.
